## Alignment gates (read this first, every session)

Durable decisions are ratified in committed docs before the work that depends on
them. The gate docs are the substrate; this section is the trigger logic that
keeps code from getting ahead of its decision.

Session start: read `docs/GATES.md` and `CHARTER.md`. `docs/GATES.md` is the
index of every gate, its status (not-started / open / ratified / superseded), and
where its detail lives. `CHARTER.md` is the project's purpose and hard
boundaries. If either is missing or stale against the code you are about to
touch, say so before proceeding.

Before an activity, confirm its gate is ratified. If it is not, stop. Do not
improvise the decision in code. In order of preference: ask the user; or, if
asked to proceed, write the gate doc, set its status to open in `docs/GATES.md`,
and get it ratified before merging the dependent work.

| Before you do this | This gate must be ratified | Where it lives |
|---|---|---|
| Add or swap a framework, datastore, host, or major dependency | Stack / Architecture ADR | `docs/adr/NNNN-*.md` |
| Build any non-trivial feature | PRD / Plan gate | `docs/prd/`, `docs/plan/` |
| Build or change a user-facing surface | DESIGN.md locked | `DESIGN.md` |
| Deploy, add or rotate a secret, or handle real user data | Deployment & Security gate | `docs/SECURITY_CHECKLIST.md`, `docs/DEPLOY.md` |

Triviality exemption. Gates protect decisions, not keystrokes. You do not need a
gate for typo and copy fixes, comment edits, dependency-free bug fixes that do
not change a contract, formatting cleanup, tests for existing behavior, or
reversible tweaks fully inside an already-ratified plan. When unsure whether
something is trivial, it is not: ask or open the gate. A change that adds a
dependency, alters a schema or API contract, touches auth, moves data, or shapes
what a user sees is never trivial.

## Durable memory lives in committed docs

Decisions and volatile state belong in version control where every tool and
teammate can read them, not in any single vendor's memory store.

- `CHARTER.md` — why this project exists and its non-goals.
- `docs/adr/` — architecture decision records. One ratified decision per file,
  append-only; supersede, never silently rewrite.
- `DECISIONS.md` — running log of smaller ratified calls.
- `docs/GATES.md` — the gate index above.
- `docs/plan/*.md` — tiered plans carrying root cause, file:line, and an effort
  or Now/Next/Later tier.
- `docs/HANDOFF.md` — one dated, superseding snapshot of current volatile state
  (live URLs, in-flight branches, next work). A new handoff replaces the old one.

Any agent-specific memory (Claude auto-memory, Cursor rules) is a thin pointer to
these committed docs, never the source of truth. If a decision exists only in a
vendor memory file, it is not ratified. Write it down here.

## Skills and loops

On a fresh project, run the `discovery` skill first: a short PM/CEO session that
writes `CHARTER.md`, `VISION.md`, and `docs/prd/`, then activates the skills and
loops this project needs.

Skills are reusable how-tos under `skills/<name>/SKILL.md` (the cross-tool
SKILL.md standard). Loops are repeatable work cycles under `loops/<name>.loop.md`;
`loops/LOOPS.md` tracks which are active. Keep the active skill set small; 8 to 12
is the ceiling before selection degrades.

| Skill | Use when |
|---|---|
| `discovery` | a fresh project or overlay needs its product vision and charter set |
| `run-gate` | an alignment gate needs to be walked and ratified before guarded work |
| `harvest` | a proven pattern in this project should be promoted up into the foundation |
| `analyze` | the committed artifacts need a consistency cross-check before a Plan ratifies or a big change merges |

| Loop | Checker | Use when |
|---|---|---|
| `plan-execute-verify` | `just build && just lint` | implementing a ratified plan slice |
| `tdd-red-green-refactor` | `just test` | building or fixing a behavior with a test |

A loop runs only if it clears the appropriateness gate in `loops/README.md`
(work repeats, verification is automated, the budget absorbs retries, real tools).

## Guardrails

Non-negotiable unless a ratified gate says otherwise.

- Branch and PR discipline. Never commit directly to a shared branch (`main`,
  `develop`). Work on a feature branch and open a PR. Never force-push a shared
  branch. Commit or push only when the user asks.
- Frozen-environment isolation. When one stack is declared frozen (a shipped
  release, a demo baseline, prod), never redeploy, migrate, or mutate it. All new
  work runs on the development stack, which must be incapable of clobbering the
  frozen one.
- Two-environment discipline. Stacks are parallel and parameterized purely by env
  var: separate compute, isolated data, separate secrets. Each self-identifies
  via `/api/health` returning app_env, version, git_sha; the UI shows an
  environment badge whenever app_env is not `prod`. Prod stays badge-free.
- Promotion is gated by a written checklist. Promote a stack to present-from or
  ship only after it passes the committed end-to-end checklist twice in a row.
- Triage findings as Now / Next / Later by P0-P3. Now blocks merge. Next is
  tracked near-term. Later is pre-GA polish. Record each with root cause and
  file:line.
- Write down accepted risks. A known risk being accepted for now is recorded with
  its reason and deferral tier. An undocumented accepted risk is just a bug.
- Config in two places stays in sync. When a value is duplicated between a
  datastore and code, changing it durably means editing both. Note the pairing.
- Secrets are env-driven placeholders, never real values. No real key, token, or
  connection string is ever committed, in any doc, script, or example.
  `.env.example` carries empty placeholders. Never blind-overwrite a secret
  bundle (a --force create replaces the whole secret); edit single fields through
  the host dashboard.
- Generalize only against real instances. Do not build abstraction or config for
  a hypothetical future case. Every generalization must be demanded by at least
  two real, existing instances. When you reach for a plugin system or a config
  layer "for later," stop and write it on the refusal list instead.

## Deploy runbook discipline

Bring a stack up in dependency order, never improvised: datastore schema and
migrations first, compute and its secrets next, and the frontend's env pointed at
the live backend URL last. The full runbook and a troubleshooting catalog live in
`docs/DEPLOY.md`. When a deploy fails, read the actual error body (curl the
endpoint, read the host log) before forming a hypothesis.

## Voice and style for all prose

- No em-dashes and no double hyphens.
- No emojis.
- Never the negation-setup pattern ("that's not X, it's Y").
- Plain, low-jargon, non-dramatic, non-sycophantic. Assume the reader has context.
- Commit messages: imperative, scoped, honest about what changed.
